Feature HashMap ConcurrentHashMap Thread Safety No Yes (bucket-level locks) Iterators Fail-fast Weakly consistent Locking None <code>synchronized</code> on bucket nodes Null Keys/Values Allowed Disallowed <p>Atomic Operations we know computeIfAbsent() : If the specified key is not already associated with a value, attempts to compute its value using the given mapping function and enters it into this map unless null.(so it will check if the key exist in map, if not it will compute its value based on provided function and then put it into the map)  and this computeIfAbsent() is also present in HashMap also, its just that concurrentHashMap provides atomic version of it. </p> <ul> <li> <p><code>computeIfAbsent(key, function)</code>:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Atomically computes a value if absent. Ideal for caching.</p> <pre><code>map.computeIfAbsent("user:1001", k -&gt; fetchFromDB(k));  
</code></pre> </li> </ul> </li> <li> <p><code>merge(key, value, remappingFunction)</code>:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Atomic updates (e.g., counters).</p> <pre><code>map.merge("counter", 1, Integer::sum);  
</code></pre> <p>here if map does not have key 'counter' it will put 1 as value, if it has that key it will take the value and add 1 to it using sum function provided. so in this case it either put the provided value or recomputes it with existing and new provided value (here recompute function is sum so will add the values)</p> </li> </ul> <p> </p> </li> </ul>

Inheritance Composition Tight coupling (changes in parent affect child) Loose coupling (change one part without breaking others) Hard to reuse (a <code>Dog</code> cannot easily reuse <code>Bird</code> behavior) Easy reuse (just include the needed component) Inflexible (cannot change behavior at runtime) Flexible (can swap components at runtime) <p>Example Problem with Inheritance: If you have <code>Bird</code> and <code>Dog</code> both extending <code>Animal</code>, but only <code>Bird</code> can <code>fly()</code>, you might end up with:</p> <pre><code>class Animal {
    void eat() { ... }
    void fly() { ... }  // But Dog can't fly!
}
</code></pre> <p>This leads to unnecessary or incorrect methods in subclasses.</p> <p>Solution with Composition:</p> <pre><code>class Flyer {
    void fly() { System.out.println("Flying..."); }
}

class Bird {
    private Flyer flyer = new Flyer();
    void fly() { flyer.fly(); }
}

class Dog {
    // No Flyer here! Only Birds can fly.
}
</code></pre> <p>Now, <code>Dog</code> doesn’t have <code>fly()</code>, and <code>Bird</code> can still fly.</p>
